aa(lp55
VOn this piece of paper
p56
aVis the history the way I learned it from my Lakota friends and family.
p57
aVThe following is a time line of treaties made, treaties broken
p58
aVand massacres disguised as battles.
p59
aVI'll begin in 1824.
p60
aVWhat is known as the Bureau of Indian Affairs
p61
aVwas created within the War Department,
p62
aVsetting an early tone of aggression
p63
aVin our dealings with the Native Americans.
p64
aa(lp65
V1851:
p66
aVThe first treaty of Fort Laramie was made,
p67
aVclearly marking the boundaries of the Lakota Nation.
p68
aVAccording to the treaty, those lands are a sovereign nation.
p69
aVIf the boundaries of this treaty had held \u2014
p70
aVand there is a legal basis that they should \u2014
p71
aVthen this is what the US would look like today.
p72
aVTen years later.
p73
aVThe Homestead Act, signed by President Lincoln,
p74
aVunleashed a flood of white settlers into Native lands.
p75
aa(lp76
V1863:
p77
aVAn uprising of Santee Sioux in Minnesota
p78
aVends with the hanging of 38 Sioux men,
p79
aVthe largest mass execution in US history.
p80
aVThe execution was ordered by President Lincoln,
p81
aVonly two days after he signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
p82
aa(lp83
V1866: The beginning of the Transcontinental Railroad \u2014
p84
aVa new era.
p85
aVWe appropriated land for trails and trains
p86
aVto shortcut through the heart of the Lakota Nation.
p87
aVThe treaties were out the window.
p88
aVIn response, three tribes led by the Lakota chief Red Cloud
p89
aVattacked and defeated the US army,
p90
aVmany times over.
p91
aVI want to repeat that part:
p92
aVThe Lakota defeat the US army.
p93
aa(lp94
V1868: The second Fort Laramie Treaty clearly guarantees
p95
aVthe sovereignty of the Great Sioux Nation
p96
aVand the Lakotas' ownership of the sacred Black Hills.
p97
aVThe government also promises land and hunting rights
p98
aVin the surrounding states.
p99
aVWe promise that the Powder River country
p100
aVwill henceforth be closed to all whites.
p101
aVThe treaty seemed to be a complete victory
p102
aVfor Red Cloud and the Sioux.
p103
aVIn fact, this is the only war in American history
p104
aVin which the government negotiated a peace
p105
aVby conceding everything demanded by the enemy.
p106
aa(lp107
V1869: The Transcontinental Railroad was completed.
p108
aVIt began carrying, among other things, large numbers of hunters,
p109
aVwho began the wholesale killing of buffalo,
p110
aVeliminating a source of food, clothing and shelter for the Sioux.
p111
aa(lp112
V1871:
p113
aVThe Indian Appropriation Act
p114
aVmakes all Indians wards of the federal government.
p115
aVIn addition, the military issued orders
p116
aVforbidding western Indians from leaving reservations.
p117
aVAll western Indians at that point in time were now prisoners of war.
p118
aVAlso in 1871,
p119
aVwe ended the time of treaty-making.
p120
aVThe problem with treaties is they allow tribes to exist as sovereign nations,
p121
aVand we can't have that.
p122
aVWe had plans.
p123
aa(lp124
V1874:
p125
aVGeneral George Custer announced the discovery of gold in Lakota territory,
p126
aVspecifically the Black Hills.
p127
aVThe news of gold creates a massive influx of white settlers
p128
aVinto Lakota Nation.
p129
aVCuster recommends that Congress find a way
p130
aVto end the treaties with the Lakota as soon as possible.
p131
aa(lp132
V1875: The Lakota war begins
p133
aVover the violation of the Fort Laramie Treaty.
p134
aV1876:
p135
aVOn July 26th,
p136
aVon its way to attack a Lakota village,
p137
aVCuster's 7th Cavalry was crushed
p138
aVat the battle of Little Big Horn.
p139
aV1877:
p140
aVThe great Lakota warrior and chief named Crazy Horse
p141
aVsurrendered at Fort Robinson.
p142
aVHe was later killed while in custody.
p143
aV1877 is also the year we found a way to get around the Fort Laramie Treaties.
p144
aVA new agreement was presented to Sioux chiefs and their leading men,
p145
aVunder a campaign known as "Sell or Starve" \u2014
p146
aVsign the paper, or no food for your tribe.
p147
aVOnly 10 percent of the adult male population signed.
p148
aVThe Fort Laramie Treaty called for at least three-quarters of the tribe
p149
aVto sign away land.
p150
aVThat clause was obviously ignored.
p151
aa(lp152
V1887: The Dawes Act.
p153
aVCommunal ownership of reservation lands ends.
p154
aVReservations are cut up into 160-acre sections,
p155
aVand distributed to individual Indians
p156
aVwith the surplus disposed of.
p157
aVTribes lost millions of acres.
p158
aVThe American dream of individual land ownership
p159
aVturned out to be a very clever way
p160
aVto divide the reservation until nothing was left.
p161
aVThe move destroyed the reservations,
p162
aVmaking it easier to further subdivide and to sell
p163
aVwith every passing generation.
p164
aVMost of the surplus land
p165
aVand many of the plots within reservation boundaries
p166
aVare now in the hands of white ranchers.
p167
aVOnce again, the fat of the land goes to wasichu.
p168
aa(lp169
V1890: A date I believe to be the most important in this slide show.
p170
aVThis is the year of the Wounded Knee Massacre.
p171
aVOn December 29,
p172
aVUS troops surrounded a Sioux encampment at Wounded Knee Creek,
p173
aVand massacred Chief Big Foot and 300 prisoners of war,
p174
aVusing a new rapid-fire weapon that fired exploding shells,
p175
aVcalled a Hotchkiss gun.
p176
aVFor this so-called "battle,"
p177
aV20 Congressional Medals of Honor for Valor
p178
aVwere given to the 7th Cavalry.
p179
aVTo this day,
p180
aVthis is the most Medals of Honor ever awarded for a single battle.
p181
aVMore Medals of Honor were given
p182
aVfor the indiscriminate slaughter of women and children
p183
aVthan for any battle in World War One,
p184
aVWorld War Two,
p185
aVKorea, Vietnam,
p186
aVIraq or Afghanistan.
p187
aa(lp188
VThe Wounded Knee Massacre is considered the end of the Indian wars.
p189
aVWhenever I visit the site of the mass grave at Wounded Knee,
p190
aVI see it not just as a grave for the Lakota or for the Sioux,
p191
aVbut as a grave for all indigenous peoples.
p192
aVThe holy man Black Elk, said,
p193
aV"I did not know then how much was ended.
p194
aVWhen I look back now from this high hill of my old age,
p195
aVI can still see the butchered women and children
p196
aVlying heaped and scattered all along the crooked gulch,
p197
aVas plain as when I saw them
p198
aVwith eyes still young.
p199
aVAnd I can see that something else died there in the bloody mud
p200
aVand was buried in the blizzard.
p201
aVA people's dream died there.
p202
aVAnd it was a beautiful dream."
p203
aa(lp204
VWith this event,
p205
aVa new era in Native American history began.
p206
aVEverything can be measured before Wounded Knee and after,
p207
aVbecause it was in this moment,
p208
aVwith the fingers on the triggers of the Hotchkiss guns,
p209
aVthat the US government openly declared its position on Native rights.
p210
aVThey were tired of treaties.
p211
aVThey were tired of sacred hills.
p212
aVThey were tired of ghost dances.
p213
aVAnd they were tired of all the inconveniences of the Sioux.
p214
aVSo they brought out their cannons.
p215
aV"You want to be an Indian now?" they said,
p216
aVfinger on the trigger.
p217
aa(lp218
V1900:
p219
aVthe US Indian population reached its low point \u2014
p220
aVless than 250,000,
p221
aVcompared to an estimated eight million in 1492.
p222
aa(lp223
VFast-forward.
p224
aV1980:
p225
aVThe longest-running court case in US history,
p226
aVthe Sioux Nation versus the United States,
p227
aVwas ruled upon by the US Supreme Court.
p228
aVThe court determined that when the Sioux were resettled onto reservations
p229
aVand seven million acres of their land were opened up
p230
aVto prospectors and homesteaders,
p231
aVthe terms of the second Fort Laramie Treaty
p232
aVhad been violated.
p233
aVThe court stated that the Black Hills were illegally taken,
p234
aVand that the initial offering price, plus interest,
p235
aVshould be paid to the Sioux Nation.
p236
aVAs payment for the Black Hills,
p237
aVthe court awarded only 106 million dollars to the Sioux Nation.
p238
aVThe Sioux refused the money with the rallying cry,
p239
aV"The Black Hills are not for sale."
p240
aa(lp241
V2010:
p242
aVStatistics about Native population today,
p243
aVmore than a century after the massacre at Wounded Knee,
p244
aVreveal the legacy of colonization,
p245
aVforced migration
p246
aVand treaty violations.
p247
aVUnemployment on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation
p248
aVfluctuates between 85 and 90 percent.
p249
aVThe housing office is unable to build new structures,
p250
aVand existing structures are falling apart.
p251
aVMany are homeless,
p252
aVand those with homes are packed into rotting buildings
p253
aVwith up to five families.
p254
aVThirty-nine percent of homes on Pine Ridge
p255
aVhave no electricity.
p256
aVAt least 60 percent of the homes on the reservation
p257
aVare infested with black mold.
p258
aVMore than 90 percent of the population lives below the federal poverty line.
p259
aVThe tuberculosis rate on Pine Ridge
p260
aVis approximately eight times higher than the US national average.
p261
aVThe infant mortality rate is the highest on this continent,
p262
aVand is about three times higher than the US national average.
p263
aVCervical cancer is five times higher
p264
aVthan the US national average.
p265
aVThe school dropout rate is up to 70 percent.
p266
aVTeacher turnover is eight times higher than the US national average.
p267
aVFrequently, grandparents are raising their grandchildren
p268
aVbecause parents, due to alcoholism,
p269
aVdomestic violence and general apathy,
p270
aVcannot raise them.
p271
aVFifty percent of the population over the age of 40
p272
aVsuffers from diabetes.
p273
aVThe life expectancy for men is between 46 and 48 years old \u2014
p274
aVroughly the same as in Afghanistan and Somalia.
p275
aa(lp276
VThe last chapter in any successful genocide
p277
aVis the one in which the oppressor
p278
aVcan remove their hands and say,
p279
aV"My god \u2014 what are these people doing to themselves?
p280
aVThey're killing each other.
p281
aVThey're killing themselves
p282
aVwhile we watch them die."
p283
aVThis is how we came to own these United States.
p284
aVThis is the legacy
p285
aVof Manifest Destiny.
p286
aVPrisoners are still born into prisoner of war camps,
p287
aVlong after the guards are gone.
p288
aVThese are the bones left after the best meat has been taken.
